            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-06-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-06-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="414" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d414">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.61351/6–148</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Senator <persName type="to">Eugene D. Millikin</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d414fn1">Chairman, Senate Committee on Finance.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-06-02">June 2,
                            1948</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Senator Millikin</hi>: Reference is again made to
                    your letter of April 20, 1948<note n="2" xml:id="d414fn2">Not printed.</note>,
                    requesting the State Department’s comments on S. 2511, a bill “Repealing section
                    202 (<hi rend="italic">e</hi>) of the Sugar Act of 1948.”</p>
                <p>In view of the fact that the intent of this section of the Act has been widely
                    misunderstood and that circumstances under which the use of this section might
                    be considered desirable now appear remote, the Department perceives no objection
                    to its repeal.</p>
                <p>The Department has been informed by the Bureau of the Budget that there is no
                    objection to the submission of this report.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Acting Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles</hi> E. <hi rend="smallcaps">Bohlen</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Counselor</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
